WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.940
Good day. I'm Norman Wildberger. Today&nbsp;
we're going to look at the educational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:14.940 --> 00:00:19.470
aspects of this new approach to&nbsp;
arithmetic that I'm proposing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:19.470 --> 00:00:25.770
which in some sense goes back to our first&nbsp;
few videos in this series many years ago now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:25.770 --> 00:00:31.860
where we're thinking about a natural number&nbsp;
as being represented by a very simple kind of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:31.860 --> 00:00:38.010
representation of marks on a piece of bark or&nbsp;
strokes on a page. We're making that a little&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:38.010 --> 00:00:46.890
bit more explicit by talking about M-sets of&nbsp;
units—unit somethings or marks—and we're basically&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:46.890 --> 00:00:53.550
employing an M-set or multiset orientation to&nbsp;
define arithmetic, for example, addition like this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:53.550 --> 00:01:01.920
or multiplication like this. We've identified this&nbsp;
type "nat," which represents multisets of marks,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:01.920 --> 00:01:09.480
and I claim that this kind of arithmetic is in&nbsp;
some sense more fundamental and more basic than&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:09.480 --> 00:01:18.000
our usual Hindu-Arabic arithmetic that we teach&nbsp;
young people involving the symbols 1, 2, 3, 6,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:24.750
and so on. There is something more primitive and&nbsp;
more elementary about this, which I think makes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:24.750 --> 00:01:31.290
it possibly attractive for educators to try&nbsp;
to instill numeracy into very young people.

00:01:31.290 --> 00:01:37.140
So today, we're going to be looking at&nbsp;
the issues of naming and ordering these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:37.140 --> 00:01:42.270
primitive natural numbers, and we want to&nbsp;
do it in a way that's largely independent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:42.270 --> 00:01:49.590
of some higher verbal facility requiring&nbsp;
understanding of these Hindu-Arabic numerals.

00:01:49.590 --> 00:01:55.170
All right, so since we're human beings,&nbsp;
we like to talk and to express ourselves&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:55.170 --> 00:02:01.800
verbally as well as by writing things&nbsp;
down. So it's natural for us to look to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:01.800 --> 00:02:07.500
having names for these simple kinds of&nbsp;
primitive natural numbers we're talking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:07.500 --> 00:02:13.380
about. So let's do that now, but perhaps in&nbsp;
a somewhat surprising and maybe naive way.

00:02:13.380 --> 00:02:26.190
All right, so our first number is 0. This is this&nbsp;
empty multiset—just brackets with a bit of empty&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:26.190 --> 00:02:33.060
space inside, okay? And we're going to give the&nbsp;
traditional name "zero" to that. And then the next&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:33.060 --> 00:02:39.600
one is what we're going to call "one." So we just&nbsp;
have a single unit something inside our M-set;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:39.600 --> 00:02:45.900
we'll call that "one." And now, what about&nbsp;
this one? Well, the temptation, of course,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:45.900 --> 00:02:52.320
is to call it "two." That's already somewhat&nbsp;
sophisticated—the idea of introducing a new&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:52.320 --> 00:03:00.870
name for every next number. What we're going to&nbsp;
do, rather, is to refer to this as "11." Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:00.870 --> 00:03:06.450
we could also call it "mark, mark" or "unit,&nbsp;
unit," but I think it's preferable to actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:06.450 --> 00:03:13.200
use "11." This is in keeping with what a young&nbsp;
person might want to do. So technically speaking,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:13.200 --> 00:03:19.320
this is actually "one plus one"; it's actually&nbsp;
what you get when you take this one and you add&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:19.320 --> 00:03:25.710
one. But let's give it a name, and let's call&nbsp;
it "11." And similarly, let's call this one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:25.710 --> 00:03:33.540
"111," and so on. You can see what the pattern&nbsp;
is. So this is, in fact, a base-one system,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:33.540 --> 00:03:41.130
if you like. We're really only going to be using&nbsp;
these two words: "zero" and "one," and everything&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:41.130 --> 00:03:50.160
else is going to be built up from just repeating&nbsp;
this particular word. And this is very much in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:50.160 --> 00:03:57.270
keeping with our expressions, what we're writing&nbsp;
down—we're really only writing down two kinds of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:57.270 --> 00:04:03.810
things: either an empty space or a mark, and&nbsp;
we're possibly repeating the marks inside our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:03.810 --> 00:04:12.570
brackets. So the verbal simplicity is reflecting&nbsp;
the written simplicity—somehow it makes sense.

00:04:12.570 --> 00:04:17.970
And of course, for a young person, learning&nbsp;
this kind of system is, relatively speaking,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:17.970 --> 00:04:23.850
a piece of cake. This is vastly simpler than&nbsp;
learning the standard Hindu-Arabic words:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:23.850 --> 00:04:27.690
one, two, three, four, five, six, seven,&nbsp;
eight, nine, ten, and then eleven, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:27.690 --> 00:04:32.970
then twelve, thirteen, and fourteen. That's&nbsp;
all reasonably complicated and takes a fair&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:32.970 --> 00:04:39.150
amount of repetition and learning. In fact,&nbsp;
it's not really logically that clear, is it?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:39.150 --> 00:04:45.360
There's something very logically clear about this&nbsp;
system, even though it may be somewhat primitive.

00:04:45.360 --> 00:04:51.570
So, for example, let us look at&nbsp;
the name of this natural number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:51.570 --> 00:05:04.350
okay? What is its name? It is "111111." That&nbsp;
is the name of this natural number. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:04.350 --> 00:05:11.100
we've talked about how the original motivation for&nbsp;
natural numbers probably arose in the context of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:11.100 --> 00:05:18.180
wanting to measure how many of a certain thing&nbsp;
there were out in the real world—maybe antelope&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:18.180 --> 00:05:28.800
at a waterhole. So this is a fundamental usage of&nbsp;
numbers: to measure the size of, well, what we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:28.800 --> 00:05:33.960
calling M-sets or multisets—collections&nbsp;
of stuff out there in the world.

00:05:33.960 --> 00:05:45.630
So, for example, here is an M-set which consists&nbsp;
of these letters, okay? So even a student who&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:45.630 --> 00:05:51.390
perhaps hasn't learned how to read can still&nbsp;
understand that these are things called letters,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:51.390 --> 00:05:58.500
and we can count them in the following&nbsp;
way: we can just go through the letters,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:58.500 --> 00:06:03.150
and wherever there's a letter, we can make&nbsp;
a mark. So for this letter, we make a mark,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:03.150 --> 00:06:10.470
then another one, another one, another&nbsp;
one, one more, one more, one more,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:10.470 --> 00:06:18.000
one more. So what we've done is we've replaced&nbsp;
each of the objects in this collection that we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:25.560
interested in with one of our simple unit marks.&nbsp;
And we can say that what we've done then is to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:25.560 --> 00:06:32.850
measure the size of this collection or M-set. So&nbsp;
the size of this M-set is this natural number.

00:06:32.850 --> 00:06:40.860
Now, M-sets in real life don't necessarily have to&nbsp;
come in these kinds of linear bracketed forms like&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:40.860 --> 00:06:45.810
this. So here might be another kind of example&nbsp;
that you could give a young person. So here is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:45.810 --> 00:06:51.360
a box of some kind, and it has certain objects&nbsp;
in it, and the objects are of the pleasant kind,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:51.360 --> 00:06:58.320
and we might be interested in how big this box is&nbsp;
in the sense of how many things are there in it.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:58.320 --> 00:07:06.270
So the young person, understanding the strategy,&nbsp;
would do the following: they would say, "Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:06.270 --> 00:07:11.460
what we're going to do is we're going to just&nbsp;
create a number out of the box by replacing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:11.460 --> 00:07:19.770
the objects in here with our unit marks." So&nbsp;
I'm going to make a mark there for this thing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:19.770 --> 00:07:25.410
a mark there for that heart, a mark there for&nbsp;
that diamond, another mark there for that diamond,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:25.410 --> 00:07:30.600
let's see, that rectangle gets a mark,&nbsp;
that heart gets a mark, that rectangle&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:30.600 --> 00:07:37.020
gets a mark, and there's a square over there—that&nbsp;
gets a mark, right? So I've replaced this multiset&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:37.020 --> 00:07:48.090
of objects with a multiset of marks. It's a&nbsp;
simplification. So measuring the size of something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:48.090 --> 00:07:54.210
is some kind of simplification where you just&nbsp;
replace objects with our fundamental unit marks.

00:07:54.210 --> 00:08:00.240
Now, this isn't really in the standard form&nbsp;
for a natural number, so we would want our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:00.240 --> 00:08:08.400
student to express this more in keeping with&nbsp;
our terminology. So then they would be obliged&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:08.400 --> 00:08:14.610
to organize these marks, right? To write them&nbsp;
down in the sequential fashion. And so they'd&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:14.610 --> 00:08:18.870
have to do this in some kind of a reasonable way&nbsp;
so they don't get confused—maybe that one there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:18.870 --> 00:08:24.990
then that one, that one, that one,&nbsp;
that one, that one, that one, that one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:24.990 --> 00:08:33.330
and then we close the set. So let's observe&nbsp;
that counting is actually not really involved&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:33.330 --> 00:08:38.580
here. It's not the case that we are counting&nbsp;
how many of these things there are—that we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:38.580 --> 00:08:44.550
have a prior verbal system for ordering numbers.&nbsp;
Rather, what we're doing is we're just replacing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:44.550 --> 00:08:54.900
objects with marks and then organizing them in&nbsp;
a linear fashion, okay? So it's really prior to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:54.900 --> 00:09:02.700
what we usually think of as counting—some kind of&nbsp;
more simple, basic, primeval kind of operation.

00:09:02.700 --> 00:09:08.700
So to measure an M-set, we just replace&nbsp;
each of its elements with a unit something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:08.700 --> 00:09:16.950
or mark—in other words, one of our little&nbsp;
strokes. That's what measuring M-sets means.

00:09:16.950 --> 00:09:23.490
Now, doing arithmetic with numbers is so familiar&nbsp;
to us and ingrained in us that sometimes we're not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:23.490 --> 00:09:31.440
even aware of relatively basic distinctions. And&nbsp;
a very important distinction is that there are at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:31.440 --> 00:09:38.640
least two different kinds of roles that numbers&nbsp;
play when we're using them to describe the world&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:38.640 --> 00:09:47.790
around us. So numbers, as we've seen, are used&nbsp;
to measure the sizes of collections or M-sets,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:47.790 --> 00:09:56.220
but they can also be used for counting in the&nbsp;
sense of ordering. And mathematicians have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:56.220 --> 00:10:03.300
names for these different kinds of usages. So we&nbsp;
talk about cardinal numbers and ordinal numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:03.300 --> 00:10:11.040
So this is somewhat fancy terminology that&nbsp;
refers to numbers being used in the context of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:11.040 --> 00:10:20.070
measuring sizes of M-sets typically, and here the&nbsp;
ordinal numbers refer to counting the position in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:20.070 --> 00:10:26.850
a list. We have something ordered, and you want&nbsp;
to refer to a particular element in that order.

00:10:26.850 --> 00:10:36.660
So let's give two examples of these different&nbsp;
usages of numbers. So a cardinal number usage&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:36.660 --> 00:10:42.750
is one that we've already been looking at.&nbsp;
So here is an M-set, the M-set {A, C, D, A},&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:42.750 --> 00:10:50.760
and we're interested in measuring how big that&nbsp;
M-set is. So that's a cardinal number usage. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:50.760 --> 00:10:58.980
we're measuring that set, and we're getting&nbsp;
that the answer is the number "1111," okay?

00:10:58.980 --> 00:11:07.290
So now here's an ordinal number usage, where we're&nbsp;
referring to not an M-set, which is a collection&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:07.290 --> 00:11:14.280
of stuff, but we're actually interested in a list.&nbsp;
So here's a list. You can tell it's a list because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:14.280 --> 00:11:20.760
it has square brackets and it has commas, and&nbsp;
so the commas are telling us that in this case,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:20.760 --> 00:11:27.240
these elements are ordered. We're starting with&nbsp;
A, and then B, and then C, and then D. Over here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:27.240 --> 00:11:32.970
there were no commas—this is an unordered&nbsp;
multiset. If we interchange the order,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:32.970 --> 00:11:38.730
things would not change. This is a list—the&nbsp;
order does matter. So the question here is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:38.730 --> 00:11:47.790
what is the "1111" element of this list? The&nbsp;
"1111"—we're talking about trying to find&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:47.790 --> 00:11:56.340
the element, not which is the one element, and&nbsp;
not the "11" element, but the "1111" element,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:56.340 --> 00:12:05.400
and we identify that that is actually C. So&nbsp;
this usage of the number "1111" is subtly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:05.400 --> 00:12:15.930
but importantly different from the usage of this&nbsp;
number "1111." Here, we're measuring the size, the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:15.930 --> 00:12:24.030
largeness of a collection or an M-set, and here&nbsp;
we're specifying the position inside some ordered&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:24.030 --> 00:12:30.810
structure, inside some kind of sequence, which&nbsp;
for us is best captured by the idea of a list.

00:12:30.810 --> 00:12:40.530
Now, this ordinal usage of numbers connects&nbsp;
naturally with a natural order on natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:40.530 --> 00:12:46.500
numbers. So we originally defined natural numbers&nbsp;
just in terms of what they are—a natural number is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:46.500 --> 00:12:55.410
an M-set of marks, and we had lots of different&nbsp;
kinds of M-sets. Now we're observing that our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:55.410 --> 00:13:04.590
natural numbers can actually be arranged in a&nbsp;
very efficient and natural way. We can list them;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:04.590 --> 00:13:12.330
we can put them in a sequence starting from the&nbsp;
smallest ones and working our way step by step,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:12.330 --> 00:13:18.480
concretely, one at a time, to bigger&nbsp;
and bigger numbers. And here, of course,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:18.480 --> 00:13:23.160
is this sequence—the ordering that we're&nbsp;
talking about, where we're starting with,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:23.160 --> 00:13:31.170
in this case, the empty M-set, or 0,&nbsp;
and then we have the M-set "1," and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:31.170 --> 00:13:45.780
then "11," and then "111," "1111," "11111,"&nbsp;
and "111111." And we can keep going. So here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:45.780 --> 00:13:53.490
the three dots refer to the fact that we can&nbsp;
go from one to the next by adding one—that is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:53.490 --> 00:14:00.030
the systematic way of going from one of&nbsp;
these to the next one, we're adding one.

00:14:00.030 --> 00:14:07.200
So that leads naturally to this terminology, which&nbsp;
is useful: the idea of a successor of a natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:07.200 --> 00:14:13.740
number. So if "K" is a natural number—let's&nbsp;
introduce some abstract letter to represent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:13.740 --> 00:14:22.500
it—then its successor is, we might introduce&nbsp;
this notation, "K prime." That means "K plus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:22.500 --> 00:14:32.400
1." So this is the number one, which consists of&nbsp;
a single mark, okay? What's inside here is not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:32.400 --> 00:14:38.850
the number one—there's a mark inside, that unit&nbsp;
something. This whole thing is the number one.

00:14:38.850 --> 00:14:45.600
So, for example, here's a number—the&nbsp;
number is "111," and its successor is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:45.600 --> 00:14:52.920
well, what you get when you take the number&nbsp;
"111" and you add one, you add a mark,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:52.920 --> 00:15:02.250
you get "1111." So that's a successor—that's&nbsp;
the successor of that. And that's really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:02.250 --> 00:15:06.390
what generates this sequence or&nbsp;
this ordering of natural numbers.

00:15:06.390 --> 00:15:14.610
Okay, so there's now a theorem here that emerges,&nbsp;
which is a pretty obvious theorem in some ways,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:14.610 --> 00:15:21.780
but it's probably useful to lay it out concretely,&nbsp;
and let's call it the "Theorem of Induction."&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:21.780 --> 00:15:28.980
So the theorem of induction is that any natural&nbsp;
number can be obtained by starting with the empty&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:28.980 --> 00:15:41.800
M-set, 0, then possibly taking successors. So&nbsp;
we've seen that we can start with 0, and then we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:41.800 --> 00:15:46.600
can take a successor, we can get one, and then we&nbsp;
can get "11," and then we get "111," and then we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:46.600 --> 00:15:52.060
get "1111," and then "11111." What we're stating&nbsp;
now is that if we had any natural number—someone&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:52.060 --> 00:15:57.130
writes down the natural number—that it actually is&nbsp;
in this sequence somewhere. That if we start with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:57.130 --> 00:16:03.610
zero, add one, add one, add one, eventually,&nbsp;
at some point, we will get to that natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:03.610 --> 00:16:09.550
number that we've written down. This sequence&nbsp;
does not miss some natural number somewhere.

00:16:09.550 --> 00:16:17.680
Okay, what is the proof case? It's close to&nbsp;
being intuitively obvious, but if we had to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:17.680 --> 00:16:23.170
write something down to convince some, maybe young&nbsp;
person, we might say the following: if the natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:23.170 --> 00:16:29.050
number that we're starting with is 0 itself, well,&nbsp;
then it is of this form—it's contained in this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:29.050 --> 00:16:35.890
prescription because it's the first thing that&nbsp;
we're starting with. If it's not 0, that means it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:35.890 --> 00:16:43.060
contains a mark, and so it can be written as the&nbsp;
successor of a number with fewer marks. In other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:43.060 --> 00:16:51.520
words, it can be written as the successor of the&nbsp;
number that we get by removing that mark. And we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:51.520 --> 00:16:56.770
can then continue to do that—we can continue to&nbsp;
find a number of which that is the successor by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:56.770 --> 00:17:04.930
again removing a mark. So we can go from a natural&nbsp;
number that's written down, we can find a finite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:04.930 --> 00:17:13.900
sequence of numbers, each of which the one that&nbsp;
you have is a successor of, and then eventually we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:13.900 --> 00:17:21.610
get back to the empty set. That's a consequence of&nbsp;
the fact that we've written down a finite number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:21.610 --> 00:17:27.760
of marks—we've written down a specific number of&nbsp;
marks, and so we're going to rub them off one at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:27.760 --> 00:17:33.280
a time. Well, that's only going to take a certain&nbsp;
number of steps—namely, the number of marks—and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:33.280 --> 00:17:41.740
then eventually we will get down to the empty set.&nbsp;
So it's a kind of argument that says, "All right,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:41.740 --> 00:17:49.540
given the natural number, we can get back to the&nbsp;
empty set in this very concrete, prescribed way."

00:17:49.540 --> 00:17:57.760
All right, so for example, here is a&nbsp;
number—it's the number "111111." And we can ask,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:57.760 --> 00:18:06.040
can this actually be obtained from the empty set,&nbsp;
or 0, by taking successors? Well, we would answer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:06.040 --> 00:18:12.040
that question one way, I think. The natural way is&nbsp;
to take the number that we're given and to write&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:12.040 --> 00:18:17.740
it as a successor of something—we write it as a&nbsp;
successor of what we get by removing one of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:17.740 --> 00:18:27.580
marks. So this is the successor of "11111." And&nbsp;
similarly, this thing is the successor of "1111,"&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:27.580 --> 00:18:34.870
what we get by removing one of the marks. This is&nbsp;
the successor of "111." This is the successor of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:34.870 --> 00:18:44.290
"11." This is the successor of "1." And this&nbsp;
is the successor of "0." So the answer is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:44.290 --> 00:18:50.110
of course, yes, and we've sort of clearly laid&nbsp;
out then what is the sequence that we have to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:50.110 --> 00:18:56.470
go through to go from original 0 to the number&nbsp;
that we're interested in. We have to go back up&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:56.470 --> 00:19:01.120
this staircase that we've just gone down.&nbsp;
So we start with 0, and then we go to 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:01.120 --> 00:19:07.030
and then "11," then "111," and then "1111,"&nbsp;
and then "11111," and then the next step,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:07.030 --> 00:19:13.390
"111111," we get to the number that we've&nbsp;
started with. So that, yes, this number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:13.390 --> 00:19:20.560
actually is in the sequence or the listing&nbsp;
or the natural ordering of natural numbers.

00:19:20.560 --> 00:19:30.490
So when I was younger, there was a very popular&nbsp;
TV show for young people called "Sesame Street."&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:30.490 --> 00:19:37.270
Maybe it is still around, with lots of funny&nbsp;
monsters and characters and so on. But they&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:37.270 --> 00:19:45.160
also had a lot of training or familiarization&nbsp;
for students with respect to numbers. So there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:45.160 --> 00:19:50.500
would be a lot of signs flashing around&nbsp;
like "1, 2, 3," the Hindu-Arabic symbols,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:50.500 --> 00:19:56.470
and, you know, one plus two is three, and three&nbsp;
plus four is seven, and so on. And I think that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:56.470 --> 00:20:03.610
great because it introduces young people to the&nbsp;
idea of numeracy and being familiar with natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:03.610 --> 00:20:08.260
numbers. But I'm not so convinced that these&nbsp;
are the first steps that young people should&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:08.260 --> 00:20:17.440
go down. I think it's possible that this kind&nbsp;
of more primitive number sense, where we just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:17.440 --> 00:20:26.560
deal with natural numbers in this primitive&nbsp;
form—"1111," "111111," and so on—that it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:26.560 --> 00:20:37.330
somehow simpler and more in keeping with trying&nbsp;
to imbue a numerical sense into young people,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:37.330 --> 00:20:45.010
independent of a verbal facility that may only&nbsp;
come later. So, in principle, I think working&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:45.010 --> 00:20:50.890
with these kinds of natural numbers could actually&nbsp;
happen at a much earlier age—maybe two years old,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:50.890 --> 00:20:56.470
three years old. We can already get young&nbsp;
people doing arithmetic in this context.

00:20:56.470 --> 00:21:03.490
So here are some exercises that we might&nbsp;
give students in this direction. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:03.490 --> 00:21:08.350
so for example, they might want to find the sizes&nbsp;
of these M-sets. So here are some collections,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:08.350 --> 00:21:15.220
and we want to write down what their sizes are.&nbsp;
And the important thing is that the students do&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:15.220 --> 00:21:21.250
not yet need to know how to count, okay? They can&nbsp;
do this before they have learned to count. They&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:21.250 --> 00:21:29.920
can write down marks for each one of these things,&nbsp;
matching up the objects with marks, very much the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:29.920 --> 00:21:36.190
same way that a primitive person at a waterhole&nbsp;
might match up antelope with X's on a piece of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:36.190 --> 00:21:47.170
bark. They can make computations like this: they&nbsp;
can calculate what is "111" plus "111111," and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:47.170 --> 00:21:51.520
they can write down the answer, and then they can&nbsp;
tell you what the answer is in the sense of, "The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:51.520 --> 00:22:02.350
answer is '1111111.'" They can do multiplication.&nbsp;
They can do addition with more than just two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:02.350 --> 00:22:09.010
things. So we can get a three-year-old to&nbsp;
understand what's being asked here and to actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:09.010 --> 00:22:19.660
make computations. We can ask them to find the&nbsp;
successor of some number like this. We can get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:19.660 --> 00:22:27.070
them to explore the ordinal aspects of numbers.&nbsp;
We can ask them for the "11111" element of this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:27.070 --> 00:22:40.210
sequence. We can ask them to verify some basic&nbsp;
law of arithmetic—what is "111" plus "111111"? Is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:40.210 --> 00:22:46.870
that the same as "111111" plus "111"? In other&nbsp;
words, if you interchange these two things,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:46.870 --> 00:22:51.910
do you still get the same thing? They can verify&nbsp;
that if you do this one first, and then you do&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:51.910 --> 00:22:56.140
this one on separate pieces of paper, and then you&nbsp;
compare, lo and behold, you get the same thing.

00:22:56.140 --> 00:23:03.040
All right, so these are just indicative kinds&nbsp;
of examples that I think suggest that it might&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:03.040 --> 00:23:11.110
be interesting to try to get young people&nbsp;
engaged in numerical intuition and actual&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:11.110 --> 00:23:17.500
computation at a very early age, at an age&nbsp;
that's before they normally do the kind of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:17.500 --> 00:23:25.420
Hindu-Arabic arithmetic that they currently&nbsp;
do. Logically and maybe pedagogically,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:25.420 --> 00:23:31.750
this primitive natural number arithmetic really&nbsp;
ought to come before the Hindu-Arabic arithmetic.

00:23:31.750 --> 00:23:37.960
In our next video, we do want to turn our&nbsp;
attention to the Hindu-Arabic arithmetic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:37.960 --> 00:23:43.990
which of course is very important and is&nbsp;
practically much more sensible than this is.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:43.990 --> 00:23:48.850
But still, it's important for us to distinguish&nbsp;
between these two kinds of things. So we want&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:48.850 --> 00:23:54.130
to make some space between this primitive&nbsp;
natural number arithmetic and the Hindu-Arabic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:54.130 --> 00:24:02.590
arithmetic. That is for several reasons, one&nbsp;
of which is that when we're talking about very,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:02.590 --> 00:24:07.630
very big numbers, then the Hindu-Arabic&nbsp;
system is actually much more powerful,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:07.630 --> 00:24:13.330
but also correspondingly more problematic&nbsp;
to deal with than the primitive one. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:13.330 --> 00:24:17.980
we're going to have to explore not just&nbsp;
the pros but also the cons of moving from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:17.980 --> 00:24:23.530
primitive natural numbers to Hindu-Arabic&nbsp;
ones. It's a bit of a trade-off, actually.

00:24:23.530 --> 00:24:28.540
I hope you'll join me for that. I'm&nbsp;
Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

